        "_comment_starttls_mx": "STARTTLS-MX probe (--deep). For each MX host we open TCP/25, EHLO, STARTTLS, and inspect the negotiated TLS version. Worst-of aggregation across hosts: an attacker can MITM the lowest-preference MX, so the weakest host defines the actual exposure. tls_1_3 → 2/2 (full credit, modern TLS); tls_1_2 → 1.5/2 (acceptable but TLS 1.3 is now widely supported and a half-point penalty rewards operators who upgrade); tls_legacy → 1/2 (TLS 1.0/1.1 negotiated; encrypted but vulnerable); no_starttls → 0/2 (server didn't advertise STARTTLS at EHLO, mail is plaintext on the wire); unprobed → 0/0 (port 25 blocked egress, connection timeout, or other network error — we couldn't conclude anything). The unprobed row is intentionally still emitted into the breakdown (rather than silently dropped) so the operator sees the check was attempted and the reason it produced no signal — silent disappearance would let an operator wrongly conclude STARTTLS is fine when it was just unprobed.",
        "STARTTLS-MX": {
            "tls_1_3": {
