    "_comment_scoring_policy_eol": "Per-library 0/1 scoring for detected EOL libraries, per-OS 0/3 scoring for detected EOL operating systems. Both implementations work the same way: score_results() in audit_checks.py iterates the relevant list (results['versioned_libs']['libraries'] for libs, results['os_eol']['os_findings'] for OSes) after all other checks and appends per-finding tuples with hardcoded weights (libraries are 0/1, OSes are 0/3). The rubric does NOT contain weight entries for these labels — they're appended directly. Category resolution falls through to 'Website' (the catch-all), which is the correct destination.",
    "_comment_starttls_mx_aggregation": "STARTTLS-MX is scored worst-CONFIRMED-of across MX hosts. Severity ordering of confirmed outcomes (worst → best): no_starttls > tls_legacy > tls_1_2 > tls_1_3. Unprobed hosts are dropped from the aggregation when ANY confirmed result exists — a network error on one host (port 25 blocked egress, timeout, refused connection) does not pull down the score for a domain where other MX hosts produced clean handshakes. Only when EVERY host was unprobed does the entire check evaluate to 'unprobed' (0/0). The 0/0 row still appears in the breakdown rather than being silently dropped, so the operator sees the check ran but produced no signal."
}
